Issues.Body:
**Info about the project:**
- Running Blazor 0.5.1, ASP.NET Core 2.1
- Blazor Server-side Project

**Issue:**
So I tried to experiment with the Task.Delay aync/await, and without it. First I tried with the usual way, async Task and then await the Task.Delay. This works fine (But locks the UI thread)

But If I remove the await from Task.Delay, Windows hangs and in the end a force shutdown is required as Windows itself don't respond.

Here's my OnInitAsync code where the Task is executed:

```
protected override async Task OnInitAsync()
    {
        forecasts = await ForecastService.GetForecastAsync(DateTime.Now);
        isRunning = true;

        Task loopTask = Task.Run(() =>
        {
            Random Ran = new Random();
            while (isRunning)
            {
                forecasts.Add(new WeatherForecast()
                {
                    Date = DateTime.Now,
                    Summary = "Bla bla",
                    TemperatureC = Ran.Next(1, 100),
                    TemperatureF = Ran.Next(1, 100)
                });
                Task.Delay(1000);
            }
        });
    }
```

Is the "Hang windows until it basically crashes" an intended feature? Shouldn't something (The Blazor ASP.NET Server) prevent this somehow?

I don't see anything mentioned in the "Component model" issue (#1), so I was wondering if there are plans to address rendering list of components.  For example:

```
    @foreach (var item in toDoListItems)
    {
        <ToDoItemComponent Item="@item" />
    }
```

As it currently stands, if I insert an item at position "i", all the existing component instances from "i" to the end of the list will have their parameter set to "i + 1", resulting in a significant number of changes instead of just one component instance being created.  The same with removing an item from a list.

Are there plans to add some sort of "key" functionality, so the framework can match up list items with their original component instances and process changes more efficiently?

I play with simple NLP application inside browser.
 I want to add loading indicator. Right now I use following approach

```
this.loading = true;
this.StateHasChanged();
try {
    this.result = await httpClient.GetJsonAsync<SearchResult[]>($"api/search/sentence?content={content}");
} finally {
     this.loading = false;
}
```

Main trick is using `StateHasChanged`. My question is: Is this correct way to do that? How Blazor in general think such cases should be handled. I'm fine with calling `StateHasChanged()` but I prefer that it would be called automatically before `await`. 


## Example 1
```
this.loading = true;
try {
    // this.StateHasChanged(); called here by runtime
    this.result = await httpClient.GetJsonAsync<SearchResult[]>($"api/search/sentence?content={content}");
} finally {
     this.loading = false;
}
```

## Example 2
or better, if I could control that using for example `.ConfigureAwait(false)`

```
this.loading = true;
try {
    // this.StateHasChanged(); called here by runtime
    this.result = await httpClient.GetJsonAsync<SearchResult[]>($"api/search/sentence?content={content}")
             .ConfigureAwait(false);
} finally {
     this.loading = false;
}
```
